  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - This and the following two verses give the houses of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Merari",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", contributing four houses, and, with the nine Gershonite and eleven Kohathite, adding up to twenty-four. Merari is the third son of Levi (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Mahli",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Mushi",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of this verse were possibly ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "grandson",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "son",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Merari, if we follow the guidance of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Yet it would seem far more natural to explain this last-quoted passage by our ver. 23, which would then parallel it. Otherwise we must account for the name of Mahli habitually standing first, as here, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " also, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 24:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as also in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 3:20, 33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; in all of which places the statement is as distinct as in this verse, that Mahli and Mushi were sons. This and the following verse must be compared particularly with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 24:26-29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Jaaziah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of which passage was evidently no son of Merari, on a par with Mahli and Mushi, but a later descendant. His descendants were three - Shoham, Zaccur, and Ibri (Beno being no proper name, but signifying \"his son\"). 1 Chronicles 23:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The fathers'-houses of the Merarites. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 23:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 3:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", two sons of Merari are mentioned-Mahli and Mushi-who founded the two families of Merari which existed in the time of Moses. Mahli had two sons, Eleazar and Kish; the first of whom, however, left behind him at his death only daughters, who were married to the sons of Kish (אחיהם, i.e., their cousins), according to the law as to daughters who were heiresses (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:6-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The descendants of Mahli, therefore, were comprehended in the one father's-house of Kish, whose head at that time (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 24:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") was Jerahmeel.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
